In recent years,
researchers have developed databases of material flows in MCCs
at the world and societal levels.
These MCCs are in mass terms, not in exergy
terms~\citep{Liu:2013ab,Cao:2017aa,Plank:2022aa,Wiedenhofer:2024aa,UN-IRP:aa}.

The Exergy Economics community~\citep{exergy_economics_website}
have assembled datasets of energy-only conversion chains (ECCs) and
exergy conversion chains (XCCs)
at the societal level
in both energy and exergy quantifications
going as far back
as 1800~\cite{Steenwyk:2022ww,Pinto:2023aa,Heun:2024aa,Brockway:2024ab}.
Data for these ECCs and XCCs are organized
in the $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices of the physical supply-use table (PSUT) framework
to describe the movement of energy through society
from primary to final to useful stages
via energy transformation processes~\cite{Heun:2018,Aramendia:2022tv}.

The unified exergy analysis of materials and energy has been
applied to the analysis and design of
chemical~\citep{Michalakakis_2021a},
steel~\citep{Hernandez:2017aa,Carmona:2019aa},
cement~\citep{Morgado:2024aa}, and
energy plants~\cite{Bejan:1996}
to quantify resource efficiency and exergy destruction.
At the sectoral level,
a unified exergy analysis of materials and energy
has been applied to the UK transport sector~\citep{Rodrigues:2022aa}.
Covering the period from 1960--2015,
the study quantifies resource productivity
by tracking improvements in passenger-kilometres per megajoule (pkm/MJ),
which increased from approximately 0.42 to 0.61~pkm/MJ
across the period of study.

At the societal level,
there are several examples of
unified exergy analysis of materials and energy.
Wall and coauthors~\citep{Wall:1987,Wall:1994,Wall:1990aa}
applied a unified exergy-based analysis to assess resource use
in Sweden, Japan, and Italy,
tracing flows from primary inputs to end-use applications.
The studies reveal low overall exergy efficiencies
(around
20\% for Sweden,
21\% for Japan, and
23\% for Italy) and
highlight substantial losses across
the material and energy conversion chains.
\citet{Carmona:2021aa} quantified global resource flows and stocks
from 1900 to 2010, from extraction to end-use.
During this period,
primary exergy use increased from 115 to 903~EJ/year,
while useful exergy rose from 9 to 148~EJ/year,
with 47\% embedded in material goods by 2010.
Resource conversion efficiency improved from 8\% to 16\%.

Previous unified exergy analyses of materials and energy
at the societal level have lacked process-level detail
in characterizing material and energy transformations.
