%------------------------------
\subsubsection{The exergy of materials}
\label{sec:exergy_of_materials}
%------------------------------

Material exergy ($B$) is the exergy of a mixture of compounds
that exist at a statepoint ($B_k$).
Material exergy is the maximum amount of work
that could be extracted
by a process that takes the mixture
to equilibrium with the reference environment,
defined by its temperature ($T_0$), pressure ($P_0$), and chemical composition.
Thus, the total exergy of a material ($B$)
is the sum of the work of four reversible processes.

\begin{table}
\footnotesize
\caption{Components of material exergy.}
\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{C C C C C}
\toprule
Name & Subscript & From & To & Constraint \\
\midrule
physical exergy & ($b_{ph}$) & $T$ and $P$ & $T_0$ and $P_0$ & without changes in the chemical composition \\
chemical exergy   & ($b_{ch}$)	& Chemical composition & Reference chemical composition & while the system remains at $T_0$ and $P_0$\\
concentration exergy & ($b_c$)  & Concentration at the statepoint & Entirely concentrated & NA\\
comminution exergy & ($b_{com}$) & Dispersed state & Cohesive state & NA\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\label{tab:material_exergy}
\end{table}


We assume that all statepoints in the example MCC
are at $T_0$ and $P_0$;
thus, physical exergy ($b_{ph}$) is zero.
(The exception is Appendix~\ref{sec:MCC_exergy},
which for illustration purposes assumes
material temperature to be different from $T_0$.)
Natural resources have a positive material exergy ($b$ in kJ/mol)
because they have a chemical composition
different from their Environment.
Comminution exergy is minimal and ignored for a material conversion chain analysis
\citep[p.~280]{Valero_2015}.
(The exception, again, is Appendix~\ref{sec:MCC_exergy},
which for illustration purposes
demonstrates communition exergy calculations.)

Reference environments can include the atmosphere,
the ocean, or the Earth's crust.
Species in reference environments are characterized
by partial pressure ($P_i = y_i P_0$) in the atmosphere,
by concentrations ($C_i$) in the ocean,
and by mole fraction ($y_i$) in the Earth's crust.
We take reference environments
from \citet[Tables~11.1--11.7]{Valero_2015}.


%..............................
\paragraph{Mixture ($m$)}
\label{sec:exergy_of_mixtures}
%..............................

The total material exergy of a mixture ($B_m$) at a statepoint is

\begin{equation}\label{eq:exergy_mixture}
   B_m = N_m b_m \, ,
 \end{equation}
%
where $B_m$ is in units of $\mathrm{kJ_m}$,
$N_m$ is the amount of the mixture
(in units of $\mathrm{mol_m}$),
and $b_m$ is the molar intensive material exergy of the mixture
(in units of $\mathrm{kJ_m/mol_m}$).

The material exergy of a mixture may be accounted for each species with

\begin{equation}\label{eq:total_exergy_mixture}
   B_m = \sum_i{{N_i}{b_i}}
       = N_m\sum_i{{y_i}{b_i}} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $N_i$ is the number of moles of compound $i$
(in $\mathrm{mol_i}$),
$b_i$ is the molar intensive material exergy
of compound $i$ (in $\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$),
and $y_i$ is the mole fraction
of compound $i$ in its mixture
(in $\mathrm{mol_i/mol_m}$).


%..............................
\paragraph{Compound ($i$)}
\label{sec:exergy_of_compounds}
%..............................

In general, the molar intensive material exergy
of compound $i$ ($b_i$) is defined as

\begin{equation}
  b_i = b_{ph,i} + b_{ch,i} + b_{c,i} + b_{com,i} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $b_{ph,i}$ is physical exergy,
$b_{ch,i}$ is chemical exergy,
$b_{c,i}$ is concentration exergy, and
$b_{com,i}$ is communition exergy.
(See \citet[p.~276]{Valero_2015}.)
All terms are in units of $\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$.
As discussed above,
physical exergy ($b_{ch,i}$) is zero for all statepoints in the example MCC,
because all statepoints are assumed to be at $T_0$ and $P_0$.
Comminution exergy is assumed small and neglected.
(See Appendix~\ref{sec:MCC_exergy} for confirmation of this assumption.)
So for the purposes of this paper,
the molar intensive material exergy of a compound is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:general_material_exergy_definition}
  b_i = b_{ch,i} + b_{c,i} \, .
\end{equation}


%..............................
\paragraph{Chemical exergy($b_{ch}$)}
\label{ssec:chemical_exergy}
%..............................

The chemical exergy of a compound ($b_{ch,i}$)
existing in the reference environment
is the potential amount of work obtainable
by decomposing the compound
to compounds and elements
in their environmentally stable forms.
If compound $i$ does not exist
in the reference environment,
then the chemical exergy is the amount of work obtained
in the reversible chemical reactions
that decompose the pure compound
to the set of compounds
in equilibrium with the environment.

This process can be decomposed into two steps:
***decomposition of compound in the environment to its most stable form of compounds and elements
including the formation of a compound from stable compounds and elements,
which is captured by Gibbs free energy.***
The reversible work produced from the first process
is the chemical exergy of the compound.

