The chemical exergy of a compound ($b_{ch,i}$) is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:chemical_exergy_definition}
  b_{ch,i} = \Delta{G_{f,i}} + \sum_{i}{n_{j}b_{ch,j}} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $b_{ch,i}$ is in units of $\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$,
$n_j$ is the number of moles of an element (in units of $\mathrm{mol_i}$),
and Gibbs energy of formation ($\Delta{G_f}$) is in units of $\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$.

$\Delta{G_{f}}$ values are taken from \citet[pp.~9.4--9.94]{Dean_1979},
\citet[Table~2]{Gibbs_formation},
and \citet[Appendix~II~B]{Tro_2006}.


%..............................
\paragraph{Concentration exergy ($b_c$)}
\label{sssec:concentration_exergy}
%..............................

The concentration exergy of a mixture ($b_{c,m}$) is the the minimum work required
to separate the mixture into pure compounds.
The definition of concentration exergy is derived from the entropy of mixing.
The entropy of a mixture ($\Delta{S_m}$) is the increase in entropy
that occurs when different substances are mixed reversibly and isothermally
and is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:specific_entropy_of_mixture_definition}
  \Delta{S_m} = -RN_m(y_{1}\ln{y_{1}} + y_{2}\ln{y_{2}} + y_{3}\ln{y_{3}} + \ldots)
          = -RN_m\sum_{i} y_{i}\ln{y_{i}} \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\Delta{S_m}$ is in units of $\mathrm{kJ/mol_m \cdot K}$,
and $R$ is the universal gas constant (in units of $\mathrm{kJ/mol \cdot K}$), and
$y_i$ are in $\mathrm{mol_i/mol_m}$.

The reference point for concentrations ($y_i$) is
the species as a pure substance,
so $y_{i,0} \equiv 1$.
The minimum work required to separate a mixture reversibly
at constant temperature and pressure is given by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:work}
    W_{min} = -T_0\Delta{S_m}
            = RT_0 N_m \sum_{i}(y_i\ln{y_i}) \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $W_{min}$ is in units of $\mathrm{kJ/mol_m}$.
The minimum work is negative
because the environment puts work
into the mixture.

The concentration exergy of a compound (as defined above)
is the reversible work needed to concentrate it to the pure state.
\citet{Valero_2015} define concentration exergy of a compound ($b_{c,i}$) as

\begin{equation}\label{eq:concentration_exergy}
  b_{c,i} = RT_0[\ln(y_i) - \ln(y_{i,0})] \, .
\end{equation}
%

Simplifying Equation (\ref{eq:concentration_exergy})
with $y_{i,0} = 1$ gives

\begin{equation}\label{eq:concentration_exergy_definition}
  b_{c,i} = R T_0 \ln(y_i) \, .
\end{equation}
%
Concentration exergy is always negative
because the pure substance
in the reference environment
becomes less concentrated
at any statepoint.


