\subsubsection{The exergy of energy}
\label{sec:exergy_of_energy}
%------------------------------

The example MCC has both material and energy inputs to processes.
We calculate the exergy of energy inputs as
shown in Equation~(\ref{eq:general_material_exergy_definition})
when the Gibbs energy of formation ()
Energy inputs are treated as we treat as materials
when the Gibbs energy of formation
($\Delta{G_{f}}$)
is available.
When the Gibbs energy of formation is not available
(such as for coal and fuel oil),
we calculate the exergy of solid fuels by


\begin{equation}\label{eq:energy_exergy_fuels}
  \varepsilon_i = [LHV_i + w h_{fg}]\phi_i + 9417s
\end{equation}
%
where $\varepsilon_i$ is the exergy of energy (in units of $\mathrm{kJ}$),
$LHV_i$ is the lower heating value of a material (in units of $\mathrm{kJ/kg}$),
$w$ is the fuel's mass fraction of moisture (in units of $\mathrm{kg/kg}$),
$h_{fg}$ is the enthalpy of evaporation of \ce{H2O} (in units of $\mathrm{kJ/kg}$),
$\phi_i$ is the ratio of exergy to energy (in units of $\mathrm{kJ/kJ}$),
the constant, 9417, is the difference in sulfur's exergy and lower heating value (in units of $\mathrm{kJ/kg}$),**** needs units ---MKH ****,
and $s$ is the mass fraction of sulfur in the fuel (in units of $\mathrm{kg/kg}$).
See \citet[Eq.~C.5a]{Kotas_1995}.


We obtain \ref{eq:energy_exergy_fuels}
and $\phi$ values from \citet[Appendix~C]{Kotas_1995}.
(See Appendix~\ref{sec:appendix_phi}
for solid and liquid fuel exergy equations.)


All other energy sources in the example MCC are electricity.
The exergy of electricity is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:electricity_exergy_definition}
  X_i = \phi_i E_i \, ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\phi_{electricity} \equiv 1$, by definition.

The total exergy of energy
at any statepoint
in a material conversion chain
is given by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:energy_exergy_definition}
  X_i = \sum_i{\phi_i E_i} \, .
\end{equation}


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{The PSUT framework and $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices}
\label{sec:psut_framework}
%------------------------------

The native data format for the CL-PFU database~\citep{Brockway:2024ab} is
the $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices of the
Physical Supply-Use Table (PSUT) framework~\citep{Heun:2018,Aramendia:2022tv}.
To date, the PSUT framework has been applied
to energy conversion chains~\cite{Heun:2019aa,Aramendia:2024ac};
this paper represents its first application
to unified exergy analysis of material and energy conversion chains.

One benefit of the PSUT framework
is that it provides a natural structure for data in
material ($M$ in mass units),
energy ($E$ in energy units), and
exergy ($B$ for material and $X$ for energy in exergy units)
conversion chains
developed in Section~\ref{sec:results}
below.
The four matrices of the PSUT framework are
the resource matrix ($\mat{R}$) which contains exogeneous inputs to a conversion chain,
the use ($\mat{U}$) and make ($\mat{V}$) matrices which
describe the consumption and production of materials and energy
by processes in conversion chains, and
the final demand matrix ($\mat{Y}$) which describes consumption
of materials and energy by economic sectors.
(See \citet[Figure~1]{Aramendia:2022tv}.)


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Material and energy conversion chains}
\label{sec:conversion_chains}
%------------------------------

To illustrate application of the exergy of materials
to societal exergy analysis,
we develop several material and energy conversion chains
using the the $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices of the PSUT framework.
First, we develop
two versions of an independent material conversion chain:
(a) A mass-only material conversion chain (MCC) that contains
    mass flows from extraction through a blast furnace
    to the Iron and steel industry
    (Section~\ref{sec:material_data})
    and
(b) an exergy version of the MCC (BCC).
Each statepoint in the independent MCC is converted to exergy
to form the BCC in accordance with
the methods discussed in Section~\ref{sec:exergy_of_materials}.

In addition, we develop two versions of an independent
energy conversion chain to supply the MCC's energy requirements:
(c) an energy conversion chain (ECC) obtained from the CL-PFU database
    as described in Sections~\ref{sec:energy_data} and~\ref{sec:ecc_for_mcc}
    and
(d) an exergy version of the ECC (XCC), also
    extracted from the CL-PFU database.
To obtain the XCC needed to supply energy to the BCC,
we perform an ``upstream swim'' from a final demand ($\mat{Y}$) matrix
populated with the energy requirements of the BCC,
as discussed in~\citet[Section~2.2.5]{Heun:2018}.

Finally, we develop
(e) a unified conversion chain (BXCC) which
    brings the exergy of materials and energy together,
    as described in Section~\ref{sec:creating_bxcc} below.


